 of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Gerbidge was born in 1354, in Paston, Norfolk, England, her father, John Gerbridge, was 9 and her mother, Elizabeth, was 10. She married Edmund Berry on 24 March 1420, in Paston, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1430, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76, and was buried in Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1354–1430":"1354–1430","1369–1433":"1369–1433","1398–Female":"1398–Surnud","1400–1479":"1400–1479","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1479":"1479","1369":"1369","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1433":"1433","Abt 1398":"umbes 1398","24 March 1420":"24. märts 1420","1354":"1354","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1382":"1382","White Friars, Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Inglismaa,